DETAILS
Capstone projects give students time and support to develop a final project representing the cumulation of their technical skills. Students are responsible for proposing, designing, developing, deploying, and presenting their project. When completed, students have a stellar project providing evidence of their skill set as a web developer.

TIMELINES
July 9 - July 27: This period of time is to meet with the client to discuss their wants and propose ideas, and for the team to brainstorm on the specifics of the website and delegate responsibilities. We strongly encourage there to be no actual coding to be completed, as the Unit 8 (Spring) technical curriculum will needed to be completed simultaneously.  
July 27 - August 21: This period of time is for designing, developing, and deploying the client’s website. Presentations of the Capstone Projects will be on August 22.

REMINDERS
Students will not be compensated for this project, leaving only expenses for the website for the client to pay for (i.e. hosting fees, security certificate fees, etc.)
Find out what the client needs, but approach them with your abilities for other options, such as an additional application development. Sometimes the clients do not know what they want, so brainstorm what you can do for the business before contacting them. 

WANTS/IDEAS FROM THE CLIENT
- Wants an overall website redesign - "I want a whole new face ... something new and upbeat that will get attention."
- Updated photos.
- She manually enters information into her MLS and SEI for her website to populate listings.
- MLS search feature (current).
- Wants users to see MLS posting main and smaller images without having to click on the image, unless they want more details (think of a larger rectangle image on top and a scrolling horizontal reel right below the larger image).
- Wants to increase visibility on Google (SEO rankings).
- Likes the current colors.

Roles:
Nathan: Front-end
Dustin: Back-end
Ryan: Project Manager/Full-Stack
